==German==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|goh|de}} {{term|bī|lang=goh}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|de}} {{m|gem-pro|*bi}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/baɪ/|lang=de}}
* {{rhymes|aɪ|lang=de}}
* {{audio|De-bei.ogg|audio|lang=de}}

===Preposition===
{{head|de|preposition|+ dative}}

# {{context|locative|lang=de}} [[by]]; [[near]]
#: ''die Bank '''bei''' der Kirche'' – “the bench '''by''' the church”
#: ''die Bäckerei '''beim''' Bahnhof'' – “the bakery '''near''' the train station”
# {{context|with a person, family, shop|lang=de}} [[at]]
#: ''Ich schlafe '''bei''' Peter.'' — “I’m sleeping '''at''' Peter’s [place].”
#: ''Ich bin '''beim''' Metzger.'' — “I'm '''at''' the butcher’s.”
# {{context|with an organization or company|lang=de}} [[for]]; [[at]]; [[in]]
#: '''''bei''' der Firma arbeiten'' — “to work '''for''' the firm”
#: ''das Arbeitsklima '''bei''' Schmidt & Co.'' — “the working atmosphere '''at''' Schmidt & Co.”
# {{context|formal|reflexive|lang=de}} [[with]]; [[on]]
#: ''Er hat es nicht '''bei''' sich.'' — “He doesn’t have it '''on''' him.”
#:: → for which usually: ''Er hat es nicht {{term|dabei|lang=de}}.''
# {{context|with an event considered certain|lang=de}} [[upon]], at the time of
#: '''''bei''' Abfahrt des Zuges'' — “'''upon''' departure of the train”
# {{context|with an event considered theoretical|lang=de}} [[in case]] of, in the event of
#: '''''bei''' Hochwasser'' — “'''incase of''' flooding”
# {{context|with a continuing activity or condition|lang=de}} [[during]]; [[while]]; during the existence of
#: '''''bei''' der Arbeit'' — “'''during''' work”
#: '''''beim''' Lesen des Textes'' — “'''while''' reading the text”
#: '''''bei''' Schnee'' — “'''when there is''' snow”
# {{context|with an item that implies an activity|lang=de}} [[over]]; [[during]]
#: '''''bei''' einem Glas Wein'' — “'''over''' a glass of wine” (that is, ''while'' drinking it)
#: '''''bei''' einem Film'' — “'''during''' a film” (that is, ''while'' watching it)
# {{context|dated|in a postal address|lang=de}} [[care of]]
#: ''Frau Tina Müller '''bei''' Firma Schmidt & Co.'' — “Mrs Tina Müller, '''care of''' Schmidt & Co.” 
# {{context|now|_|dialectal|nonstandard|western and northern Germany|with <u>accusative</u>|lang=de}} [[with]], [[to]], [[towards]]
#: ''Leg dat '''bei''' die andern Sachen!'' — Put that with the other things!
#: ''Komm ma '''bei''' mich!'' — Come to me!

====Usage notes====
* When {{term|bei}} is followed by the definite article {{term|dem||the|lang=de}}, the two words contract to {{term|beim|lang=de}}. However, when {{term|dem|lang=de}} is a demonstrative pronoun, no contraction occurs. Compare:
:: ''Der Baum steht zu nah '''beim''' Haus.'' – “The tree is too close to the house.”
:: ''Der Baum steht zu nah '''bei dem''' Haus da hinten.'' – “The tree is too close to that house over there.”
* {{sense|with, to, towards}} In many dialects, and historically in literary style, {{term|bei}} could express movement, requiring then the accusative case. This is in conflict with modern standard rules, for which reason this usage is becoming rare. Note, however, that the adverb {{term|dabei|lang=de}} is still fairly common in regional speech: ''Kommt noch was '''dabei'''?'' – “Do you want anything else with that?” (for which {{term|dazu|lang=de}} is proper standard). —  Modern standard German features some relicts of the earlier usage in compounds such as {{term|herbei|lang=de}}, {{term|beiseite|lang=de}}, {{term|beilegen|lang=de}}, {{term|beitreten|lang=de}}, etc. Compare also the idiom “{{term|Butter bei die Fische|lang=de}}”. Compare further {{etym|nl|-}} {{term|bij|lang=de}} for which all such constructions are perfect standard.

